\abstract{ % An abstract of less than 150 words.
  Infectious disease transmission rates vary over time due to temporal
  changes in the environment, host population behaviour, and pathogen
  characteristics such as transmissibility and virulence.  Variation in
  the transmission rate is not observed directly but has a large effect
  on patterns of recurrent epidemics, motivating algorithms for
  estimating transmission rates from time series of observed case
  counts.  Rigorous statistical algorithms, such as iterated filtering,
  are well documented but computationally expensive, tending to scale
  poorly to longer time series.  Here, we present an \R{} package,
  \CRANpkg{fastbeta}, that implements a fast, non-probabilistic
  algorithm for back-calculating time-varying transmission rates from
  incidence time series.  We highlight additional tools provided by the
  package, including a function for efficient SEIR model simulation and
  an implementation of the Richardson-Lucy deconvolution used to
  recover incidence from reported incidence conditioned on a delay
  distribution.
  %% If we can devise a fastbeta-pomp example, then we should include
  %% it and mention it here.
}

