\section{Introduction}

%% Rt: EpiNow2, EpiEstim, EpiLPS, R0,
%%         nbTransmission, ern, Bernadette, ... ??
%% beta: fastbeta, Bernadette, ... ??
%% generic: macpan2, CollocInfer, pomp
%% even more generic: numerical integration + optim

Estimation, simulation, and analysis of compartmental mathematical
models are fundamental tasks in infectious disease epidemiology.
A critical parameter of any such model is the infectious disease
transmission rate, measuring how readily a disease spreads within a
host population.  The transmission rate changes over time in response
to factors such as weather, public health interventions, and pathogen
evolution, and these changes can have a profound influence on disease
dynamics---on the number of people infected during an epidemic, the
time scale over which an epidemic occurs, and patterns of epidemic
recurrence.  Accordingly, accurate knowledge of the transmission rate
can be used to calibrate epidemic forecasts, to inform public health
planning, and to discriminate between hypotheses about the mechanisms
that give rise to observed dynamics.

A barrier to practical consideration of transmission rates is
uncertainty.  Direct observation requires knowledge of the chain of
transmission---who infected whom and when---which is rarely available
outside of sexually transmitted diseases of humans.  In practice, the
transmission rate as a function of time must be estimated as a latent
variable from time series of observed disease incidence (counts of
infections) or disease mortality (counts of deaths from infection).




\section{The \texorpdfstring{$SE^{m}I^{n}R$}{SE\{m\}I\{n\}R} model}
\label{sec:seir}

The algorithm for transmission rate back-calculation implemented in
\CRANpkg{fastbeta} assumes that spread of the infectious disease of
interest in the population of interest can be represented by a
compartmental $SE^{m}I^{n}R$ model formulated with time-varying rates of
birth, death, and transmission---that is, an $SEIR$ model in which the
$E$ and $I$ compartments are partitioned into $m$ and $n$ stages,
respectively, for positive integers $m$ and $n$.  As a system of
ordinary differential equations, this model is expressed as
%
\begin{subequations}
\label{eq:seir}
\begin{align}
  \frac{\text{d} S}{\text{d} t}
  &= \nu(t) + \delta R - \beta(t) S \sum\nolimits_{j} I^{j} - \mu(t) S \\
  \frac{\text{d} E^{1}}{\text{d} t}
  &= \beta(t) S \sum\nolimits_{j} I^{j} - m \sigma E^{1} - \mu(t) E^{1} \\
  \frac{\text{d} E^{i}}{\text{d} t}
  &= m \sigma E^{i-1} - m \sigma E^{i} - \mu(t) E^{i} \\
  \frac{\text{d} I^{1}}{\text{d} t}
  &= m \sigma E^{m} - n \gamma I^{1} - \mu(t) I^{1} \\
  \frac{\text{d} I^{j}}{\text{d} t}
  &= n \gamma I^{j-1} - n \gamma I^{j} - \mu(t) I^{j} \\
  \frac{\text{d} R}{\text{d} t}
  &= n \gamma I^{n} - \delta R - \mu(t) R
\end{align}
\end{subequations}
%
where $S$, $E=\sum_{i=1}^{m} E^{i}$, $I=\sum_{j=1}^{n} I^{j}$, and $R$
are the numbers of individuals who are susceptible, exposed (infected
and not infectious), infectious, and recovered with immunity,
respectively, so that $N = S + E + I + R$ is the population size.

The functional parameters are $\nu(t) \geq 0$, the birth rate;
$\mu(t) \geq 0$, the natural mortality rate; and $\beta(t) \geq 0$, the
transmission rate.  The constant parameters are $\sigma > 0$,
$\gamma > 0$, and $\delta \geq 0$.  $\delta$ is a rate of loss of
immunity, allowing for reinfection of recovered individuals.

Equations \eqref{eq:seir} admit a corresponding continuous time Markov
process, in which the latent and infectious periods conditioned on
survival until recovery are Erlang-distributed with means $1/\sigma$ and
$1/\gamma$:
%
\begin{subequations}
\label{eq:erlang}
\begin{align}
  T_\text{lat} \sim& \mathrm{Erlang}(k=m, \lambda=m \sigma) \\
  T_\text{inf} \sim& \mathrm{Erlang}(k=n, \lambda=n \gamma)
\end{align}
\end{subequations}
%
The probability density function corresponding to
$\mathrm{Erlang}(k, \lambda)$ (a restriction of the gamma family
$\mathrm{Gamma}(k, \lambda)$ to integer $k$) is given by
%
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:erlang-pdf}
f(\tau; k, \lambda) = \frac{\lambda^{k}}{(k - 1)!} \tau^{k - 1} \exp(-\lambda \tau)\,,\quad k \in \{1, 2, \dots\}\,, \lambda > 0
\end{equation}
%
(see Figure~\ref{fig:erlang-pdf}).
%
<<erlang-pdf, echo=FALSE>>=
fig.begin(width = 6, height = 3)
x <- seq.int(0, 4, by = 0.01)
k <- 1:8
s <- matrix(k, nrow = length(x), ncol = length(k), byrow = TRUE)
y <- dgamma(x, shape = s, rate = s)
matplot(x, y, type = "n",
        xlab = "$\\tau$", ylab = "density, $f(\\tau; k, \\lambda)$")
abline(v = 1)
matlines(x, y, lwd = 2, lty = 1:5, col = 2:7)
legend("topright", lwd = 2, lty = 1:5, col = 2:7,
       bty = "n", cex = 0.8, legend = sprintf("$k = %d$", k))
fig.end()
